## v1.3.0 (2026-06-13)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus output.log root-cause fixes — 5 parallel sub-agents in worktrees, 2026-06-13
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- Expanded `description` triggers to (8) doing ANY multi-fix work in a shared checkout that a
  concurrent foreign session/automation may also touch — use dedicated worktrees from the start.
- Added Phase 3b "Prereq-Stacking for a Fan-Out Sharing a Common Blocker" — land the shared
  prerequisite as its OWN PR first, branch each fix off the prereq branch, target each PR at the
  prereq branch (`gh pr create --base <prereq-branch>`); GitHub auto-retargets to main once the
  prereq merges. A fix depending on another fix branches off THAT fix's branch.
- Added Phase 3c "Recovery — Work Tangled on the Wrong Branch (Foreign-Session Hijack)" — the
  patch-export safety-net recovery (`git diff --cached > /tmp/work.patch`, stash, fresh worktree,
  `git apply --check` then `git apply`, commit).
- Added "Dispatch Hygiene" sub-section: one issue + one worktree + one sub-agent per fix; all
  worktrees up front; launch all sub-agents in ONE message; per-agent brief contents.
- Added "Safety-Net Friction" sub-section: CC Safety Net blocks `git checkout -- <files>`,
  `git branch -D`, `git stash drop` — use `git stash push -- <files>`, `git branch -d`, and leave
  stashes undropped.
- Added a "Concurrent Foreign Session" warning to Phase 9 / When-to-Use: a separate
  automation/agent session in the same shared checkout can move your branch and commit under you.
- Added 2 Failed Attempts rows: multi-fix work in the shared main checkout (foreign session moved
  branch + committed); branching all N fixes off main when they share a blocker.
- Added Verified On row for ProjectHephaestus output.log root-cause fixes (5 sub-agents, 6 PRs).
- Bumped version 1.2.0 -> 1.3.0 (minor — new phases/sections/failures, no breaking changes).
- Updated `date` to 2026-06-13.

NOTE: The skill's frontmatter `verification` field remains `verified-ci` (it reflects the
prior CI-verified body). The v1.3.0 additions in this entry are **verified-local** — observed
this session in ProjectHephaestus but not yet independently CI-confirmed. New sections are
marked `(v1.3.0, verified-local)` inline so the new material is not overclaimed as verified-ci.

### Why

While shipping 6 root-cause fix PRs in ProjectHephaestus, two new failure modes surfaced that
the prior versions did not cover:

1. **Concurrent foreign session on the shared checkout.** Implementing fixes directly in the
   MAIN repo checkout (not a worktree), a separate automation/agent session running in the same
   repo committed to the working directory and switched the branch out from under the session —
   staged work landed on the wrong branch and a foreign commit appeared. Lesson: when ANY other
   session/automation may touch the shared checkout, do ALL multi-fix work in dedicated worktrees
   from the start; the worktree gives an independent HEAD/index a foreign session cannot move.
   Recovery: export the staged diff to a patch, stash to clean the branch, create the correct
   branch in a fresh worktree off the intended base, `git apply` the patch, commit.

2. **Prereq-stacking for a fan-out sharing a common blocker.** When all N fixes need a common
   prerequisite (e.g. a repo-wide format-drift fix that otherwise blocks every commit), land the
   prerequisite as its OWN PR first and branch each fix off the prereq branch, targeting each PR at
   the prereq branch. GitHub auto-retargets them to main once the prereq merges. This is how 6
   fixes shipped cleanly as a stack. Branching all N off main first means every commit is blocked
   by the unfixed shared prerequisite.

Also captured: dispatch hygiene (one issue/worktree/sub-agent per fix; all worktrees up front;
all sub-agents in one message) and CC Safety Net friction (`git checkout -- `, `git branch -D`,
`git stash drop` blocked — use the recoverable alternatives).

